# WHAT IT IS
#   nsecBunker is a NIP-46 remote signer ("bunker") for Nostr.  A
#   user's nsec (private key) lives only inside the daemon, never
#   on client devices; remote clients ask the bunker over a
#   Nostr-relay-mediated channel to sign events on their behalf,
#   subject to admin-approved policies.  The daemon (`nsecbunkerd`)
#   manages one or more named keys, accepts NIP-46 connect requests,
#   gates them through the configured admin npub(s), persists state
#   in a JSON config (default `config/nsecbunker.json`), and uses
#   `nostr-tools` v1.17.0 plus `@nostr-dev-kit/ndk` to publish /
#   subscribe across the configured relay set.  The reference
#   client (`nsecbunker-client`) exercises the wire protocol — it
#   takes a remote bunker npub, persists a local short-lived signer
#   key under `~/.nsecbunker-client-private.key/private.key`, and
#   exposes the `sign` and `create_account` flows.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from src/index.ts yargs chain +
#                       src/client.ts argv parser — extracted from
#                       upstream via `gh api repos/kind-0/
#                       nsecbunkerd/contents/...`)
#
#   nsecbunkerd — the daemon:
#     nsecbunkerd [GLOBAL OPTIONS] <SUBCOMMAND> [args...]
#
#     Global options (every subcommand):
#       -c, --config <PATH>          Path to config file
#                                    [default: config/nsecbunker.json]
#
#     Subcommands:
#       setup                        Setup nsecBunker (interactive
#                                    wizard — generates the daemon
#                                    pubkey, persists the initial
#                                    admin npub set, writes the
#                                    config file)
#
#       start                        Start nsecBunker daemon
#         -v, --verbose                Run with verbose logging
#         --key <NAME>                 Name of key to enable
#                                      (repeatable; defaults to all
#                                      configured keys when omitted)
#         -a, --admin <NPUB>           Admin npub  (repeatable;
#                                      merged with $ADMIN_NPUBS
#                                      env-var CSV)
#
#       add                          Add an nsec
#         -n, --name <NAME>            Name of the nsec  (required —
#                                      becomes the key handle that
#                                      `start --key <NAME>` filters
#                                      on)
#
#     Standard yargs auto-flags:
#       --help                       Show help
#       --version                    Show version
#
#   nsecbunker-client — reference client:
#     nsecbunker-client <COMMAND> <REMOTE-NPUB> [<CONTENT>] [OPTIONS]
#
#     Commands:
#       ping                         Liveness check against the
#                                    remote bunker  (documented in
#                                    usage; switch case currently
#                                    commented out in upstream)
#       sign                         Ask the bunker to sign — if
#                                    <CONTENT> parses as JSON,
#                                    treats it as a partial event
#                                    (kind required, no need for
#                                    pubkey or id); otherwise wraps
#                                    it as a kind:1 note tagged
#                                    `["client","nsecbunker-client"]`
#       create_account               Ask the bunker to create an
#                                    account — <CONTENT> is
#                                    `[<desired-nip05>[,<domain>
#                                    [,<email>]]]`;  <REMOTE-NPUB>
#                                    may be `<user>@<domain>` and
#                                    will be resolved via
#                                    `NDKUser.fromNip05`
#
#     Options:
#       --dont-publish               Print signature only; do not
#                                    publish the signed event to
#                                    relays
#       --debug                      Verbose debug output
#       --relays <CSV>               Comma-separated extra relays
#                                    appended to the default
#                                    `wss://relay.nsecbunker.com`
#       --pk <KEY>                   Override the persisted local
#                                    private key
#                                    (~/.nsecbunker-client-private.
#                                    key/private.key)
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   Direct dependency on `nostr-tools ^1.17.0` declared in
#   package.json — `nostr-tools` is THE canonical Node Nostr
#   protocol library, maintained by fiatjaf and the nostr-protocol
#   org (nbd-wtf/nostr-tools, 1800+ stars; the predominant typed
#   Nostr client in the Node ecosystem, used by Damus web, Iris,
#   Coracle, Snort, every NDK-based application, and most NIP-46
#   bunker clients).  nostr-tools exposes `getPublicKey`,
#   `getEventHash`, `signEvent`, `verifySignature`, the
#   `SimplePool` relay-set primitive with `pool.publish(relays,
#   event)` / `pool.list(relays, filters)` / `pool.sub(relays,
#   filters)`, every NIP-19 bech32 codec
#   (npub/nsec/note/nevent/nprofile/naddr) via
#   `nip19.decode` / `nip19.encode`, NIP-04 encrypted DM helpers
#   (`nip04.encrypt`/`nip04.decrypt`), NIP-44 v2 encrypted payloads
#   (`nip44.encrypt`/`nip44.decrypt`), NIP-26 delegation, NIP-42
#   client-auth, NIP-49 ncryptsec, and the typed `Event<K>` /
#   `Filter` / `Relay` schemas.  nsecbunkerd's `src/daemon/...`
#   uses `nostr-tools` for NIP-19 key parsing
#   (`nip19.decode(nsec)`), for raw `Event` validation, and for
#   the schnorr signing primitives behind every signed
#   NIP-46-encrypted response.  Verified via:
#     gh api repos/kind-0/nsecbunkerd/contents/package.json
#       → "nostr-tools": "^1.17.0"
#       → "@nostr-dev-kit/ndk": "workspace:*"
